        "markerKey": "web-extension-book-seven-god-s-messenger-salih-his-tribe-thamud-thamudic-rock-paintings-inscriptions-the-remnants-of-their-prehistoric-houses:web-extension:1",
        "origin": "web-extension",
        "content": "<p> The high opinion they held of Ṣāliḥ was not just flattery but is similar to the stance Quraysh took with the Prophet Muḥammad before his Messengerhood, when he was, by consensus, the best of his people, the trustworthy one (<em>al-Amīn</em>), and the perfect arbitrator. Before his Prophecy, the Prophet Muḥammad’s uncle Abū Lahab had held hopes that the Prophet would grow up to serve him and help him foster the cult of idolatry in Mecca. If either Ṣāliḥ or the Prophet Muḥammad had been willing to give up their messages and not oppose their notables, their peoples would have been willing to make them their most prominent leaders and give them anything they desired. </p>",
        "sectionId": "web-extension-book-seven-god-s-messenger-salih-his-tribe-thamud-thamudic-rock-paintings-inscriptions-the-remnants-of-their-prehistoric-houses"
